SICP First Edition Examples
===========================

Program examples from:

  Harold Abelson and Gerald Jay Sussman with Julie Sussman.
  Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs.
  Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press, 1985.  ISBN 0-262-01077-1.

Source: CMU AI Repository (1995)
  https://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/project/ai-repository/ai/lang/scheme/bookcode/sicp/

The first edition predates R4RS and uses MIT Scheme conventions.
Load sicp-compat.scm first to get the compatibility definitions
(nil, t, sequence, princ, print, 1+, -1+, atom?, cons-stream,
head, tail, the-empty-stream, etc.).

  (load "sicp-compat.scm")
  (load "chapter1.scm")

Each chapter file contains all examples from that chapter, marked
with ;;; Section N.N.N comments.  Definitions are cumulative and
often redefined (e.g., factorial appears in several variants).

Chapter 1: Building Abstractions with Procedures
Chapter 2: Building Abstractions with Data
Chapter 3: Modularity, Objects, and State
Chapter 4: Metalinguistic Abstraction (metacircular evaluator, logic programming)
Chapter 5: Computing with Register Machines (simulator, compiler)

Note: Chapters 4 and 5 are self-contained systems (a Scheme interpreter
and a register-machine simulator) that define their own eval/apply.
They are not meant to be loaded into a running session alongside
chapters 1-3.


Compatibility Layer (sicp-compat.scm)
--------------------------------------

The chapter files are unmodified from the CMU source.  All adaptations
from MIT Scheme to MScheme's R4RS live in sicp-compat.scm:

  nil, t            MIT Scheme booleans -> '() and #t
  sequence          (sequence e1 e2 ...) -> (begin e1 e2 ...)
  princ, print      MIT Scheme output -> display, write+newline
  1+, -1+           MIT Scheme arithmetic primitives
  atom?             (not (pair? x))
  runtime           MIT Scheme process timer -> MScheme's timenow
  cons-stream,      MIT Scheme lazy streams implemented via
    head, tail,       MScheme's delay/force
    the-empty-stream,
    empty-stream?
  assq              Override: returns '() on miss (MIT Scheme
                      convention) instead of #f (R4RS).  SICP's
                      chapter 3 table code tests (null? (assq ...))
                      which would crash on #f.
  sicp-random       (random n) returning integer 0..n-1


Test Suite (run-tests.scm)
---------------------------

113 tests covering all five chapters.  Run with:

  cd sicp-examples
  mscheme run-tests.scm

The test suite copies definitions verbatim from the chapter files and
adds assert-equal checks.  The following items are intentionally skipped:

  Chapter 1
    (define (p) (p))          Infinite loop (used to illustrate
                                applicative vs. normal order).

  Chapter 2
    Redefinitions of + and *  The generic arithmetic system redefines
                                the built-in arithmetic operators.
                                Loading these would break the rest
                                of the session.
    put/get dispatch table    Used in the data-directed programming
                                sections but defined later in chapter 3.
                                Tests that depend on put/get are deferred
                                to the chapter 3 section.
    put-coercion,             Referenced but never defined in the CMU
      get-coercion              source (left as exercises).

  Chapter 3
    Standalone expressions    Expressions like (set-front-ptr! ...)
                                that modify earlier data structures
                                without a testable return value.

  Chapter 4
    eval/apply redefinition   The metacircular evaluator redefines
                                eval and apply.  The test suite
                                exercises the evaluator's internals
                                (lookup, extend-environment, etc.)
                                without installing the full eval loop.
    collect macro             Used in the logic programming section
                                but never defined in the CMU source.

  Chapter 5
    define-machine DSL        Register machine definition macro; a
                                DSL-within-a-DSL that would require
                                its own macro system to run.
    =zero?,                   Referenced in the compiler section but
      greatest-common-divisor   left as exercises or assumed from
                                earlier context not present in the
                                extracted code.
